":"Names \"only son John\" (I00091); appoints wife executor; calls Gov. Robert Treat \"my honorable uncle.\"","notes":"Names \"only son John\" (I00091); Wife to take care to bring him up and educate him in the fear of God; Calls Governor Robert Treat \"my honorable uncle\" — Treat was uncle by marriage through William Fowler's wife Mary Tapp"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"character","header":"Destroyed a Wepawaug fort — fined £10","body":"In 1671, John Fowler was among the young men of Milford who destroyed the Wepawaug Indian fort — an act of colonial mischief for which he and Joseph Platt were tried by the New Haven General Court, fined £10 each, and ordered to rebuild it."},{"number":2,"category":"death","header":"Killed taking an Indian fort — 1693","body":"John Fowler died around 1693 in the taking of an Indian fort during King William's War. His will named his \"only son John\" and called Governor Robert Treat his \"honorable uncle.\" His widow Sarah remarried Capt. Samuel Newton four years later."}],"bio":{"display_name":"John Fowler","first_name":"John","last_name":"Fowler","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"john-fowler"},"X00097":{"id":"X00097","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"is_progenitor":false},"parents":{"father_research_notes":"Thomas Welch of Milford — one of the Seven Pillars of the Milford church"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00096","children_ids":["I00091"],"marriage_number":1,"location_country":"United States"},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"H00011","date_year":1697,"date_month":1,"date_day":1,"location_country":"Unit